    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nIf 'autoread' is enabled on e.g. a log file which is written by Nvim or one of its plugins, this may cause a recursive loop if an event handler / autocmd listens to buffer events which also log to the same file.\n\n\n\nAlthough https://github.com/neovim/neovim/pull/37971  implements a debounce, I haven't tested how it handles a recursive situation as described above. cc @OleksandrChekhovskyi \n\nref https://github.com/neovim/neovim/issues/1380\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nNot sure of the best way to handle this. It can be quite disruptive because it can fill up disk/RAM quickly, so we can't just depend on plugins to carefully avoid it.\n\nSome ideas:\n\n- if the file was already autoread in the last X seconds, *disable autocmds* (`'eventignore'`, `:noautocmd`, ...?) when loading the buffer this time.\n- ?",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "With the file watcher based `autoread`, it is indeed possible in theory to hit this loop. However, consider the following:\n1. This is a very narrow fringe case - you'll need to set up some kind of autocmd that would trigger on buffer reload, logs to a file, and you'll need to have that exact log open in nvim itself. It's a rather elaborate setup, no way you'd hit that by accident (maybe nvim developers could hit that realistically, but that's about it).\n2. Reload is debounced by 100ms, so it's not going to be a catastrophic explosion of reloads on ever-growing file. It'll grow, but at a \"reasonable\" pace.\n3. If you see such pathological growth, you can simply opt out with `:setlocal noautoread`.\n4. Disabling autocmds on reload might not be wise - could interfere with anything else that might want to be notified of buffer reloads (LSPs, syntax highlighting, or whatever else neovim itself or the plugins could be doing).\n\nSo the only practical thing that *could* be done is to try and detect such loop in the autoread module, and stop the watcher after threshold automatically. However, I consider this to be over-engineering for this extremely narrow case. Not worth it, my recommendation is \"do nothing, ship as is\".",
